\begin_layout Example*
the set of rational numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is a group under addition; the non-zero elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 form a group under multiplication, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
The real numbers and complex numbers are groups under addition.
 The non-zero real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and non-zero complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

 are groups under multiplication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
The complex numbers of unit modulus form a group under multiplication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,-1\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a group under multiplication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,-1,i,-i\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a group under multiplication.
\end_layout

