Subgroup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a groud and 
\begin_inset Formula $H\subset G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
1.
 (identity) 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 contains the unit element 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x,y\in H$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 (closure) and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}$
\end_inset

 (inverse) are elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar endofsentence

\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is itself a group in its own right (associativity is automatically satisfied),
 the law of composition in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 being the same as that in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the unit element of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 constitutes the a subgroup called the 
